Predicting the Price of Used Cars - Data Analysis Project - Abner Nole¶

In this project, i will use the dataset from kaggle, the links is :https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/austinreese/craigslist-carstrucks-data. And to be able to predict used cars market value can help both buyers and sellers. There are lots of individuals who are interested in the used car market because they wanted to sell their car or buy a used car.

For predict i will divided the project Preprocessing , EDA , Treatment of outliers , Feature Selection, Model development like Linear Regression,Random Forest Regressor and Gbt Regressor Model. At the end will conclude what model is the best for our dataset.

Treatment of outliers¶

  • Price column

This is a dataset about used cars, some cars their price are less than 100 dollars others exceed 1000000 dollars due to the fact that there was a registration error. We will filter out the top 1% of the highest prices in the dataset. We create a method of removing outliers from the dataset.

In [11]:
# Let's declare 2 variables that will be equal to the 0.99 and 0.01 percentile of the 'Price' variable
q = new_dataset['price'].quantile(0.99)
v = new_dataset['price'].quantile(0.01)

f_data = new_dataset[(new_dataset['price']>v) & (new_dataset['price']<q)]

Feature Selection¶

Feature selection simplified models, improves speed and prevent a series of unwanted issues arising from having many features

In [22]:
# the code help us to understand which columns have a strong correlation with the log_price column and can be used to build a better model.
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
temp_data = clean_data.copy()
for col in temp_data.columns:
    if temp_data[col].dtypes == 'object':
        encoder = LabelEncoder()
        temp_data[col] = encoder.fit_transform(temp_data[col])
        
print(abs(temp_data.corrwith(temp_data['log_price'])).sort_values(ascending=False)[1:])

Model Development¶

Declaring dependent and independent variable¶

In [23]:
#we remove the columns that will not use and left with only 'odemeter' and 'year' columns.
x = clean_data.drop(['log_price','region','model','manufacturer','condition','cylinders','fuel','image_url','description','state','posting_date'],axis=1)
y = clean_data['log_price']

Training and testing data¶

In [24]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x,y,test_size=0.2, random_state=0)
print (x_train.shape, y_train.shape)
print (x_test.shape, y_test.shape)

Random Forest Regressor Model¶

In [25]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
rf = RandomForestRegressor()


rf.fit(x_train,y_train)


y_pred_rf = rf.predict(x_test)

r_squared = r2_score(y_test,y_pred_rf)
rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test,y_pred_rf))
print("R_squared :",r_squared)
print("RMSE :",rmse)

R_squared : 0.7056808997158434
RMSE : 0.5028584423096173

Select The Best Model for the dataset¶

Random Forest Regressor is a good choice as it performs well on a wide range of datasets. Based on the R-squared and RMSE values, Random Forest Regressor has the best performance among these three models.

In [32]:
# Finally, let's manually check these predictions
# To obtain the actual prices, we take the exponential of the log_price
df_ev = pd.DataFrame(np.exp(y_pred_rf), columns=['Predicted Price'])

# We can also include the Actual price column in that data frame (so we can manually compare them)
y_test = y_test.reset_index(drop=True)
df_ev['Actual Price'] = np.exp(y_test)

# we can calculate the difference between the targets and the predictions
df_ev['Residual'] = df_ev['Actual Price'] - df_ev['Predicted Price']
df_ev['Difference%'] = np.absolute(df_ev['Residual']/df_ev['Actual Price']*100)

pd.set_option('display.float_format', lambda x: '%.2f' % x)
df_ev.sort_values(by=['Difference%'])

Conclusions:¶

Based on the analysis and modeling that we have done, we can make the following conclusions:

*The dataset contains a lot of missing values and outliers, so it was necessary to clean and preprocess the data before building models.

*The distribution of the target variable (price) is right-skewed, so it was transformed using the logarithm function to make it more normal.

*The correlation matrix and the pairplot showed that the log_price variable has a positive correlation with the year and odometer variables.

*The scatter plot of log_price vs year and log_price vs odometer showed that there is a positive linear relationship between log_price and year and log_price and odometer.

*The Random Forest Regressor model has a good R-squared of 0.70 and a low RMSE of 0.5 which makes it a good model for the dataset.

*The Linear Regression Model has a low R-squared of 0.38 and a high RMSE of 0.72 which makes it not a good model for the dataset.

*The Gradient Boosting Regressor has a R-squared of 0.53 and a RMSE of 0.63 which makes it a good model for the dataset but not as good as the Random Forest Regressor.

Overall, the Random Forest Regressor model is the best model for this dataset, it has the best R-squared and RMSE values, indicating that it is making accurate predictions.

We can use this model to predict the prices of new cars based on the input features.It's important to note that this analysis is based on a specific data, if you want to use the model in production, we should retrain the model with more recent data.
